<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05020a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05020a">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05020a"> 20(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> haunted (bed)chamber</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> Will the orthodox Christian, then, be good enough to say whether the incarnation of the Holy Ghost was a preliminary to the incarnation of Jesus Christ? It passes all comprehension how a ghost, while remaining a ghost, could become a physical father; and if the phenomenon is possible, it behoves us to be careful of <mark>haunted bedchambers</mark>. <small> G.W. Foote, <a name="BROM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BROM"><cite title="source">Bible Romances</cite></a>, 4th ed. (1922) [A Virgin Mother] 186</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c02021f" href="c02all.htm#c02021f">VI.C.02:021(f)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
